<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-7579490306358289028'>
<p>
To the anonymous guy who commented on the inverse square law:<BR/><BR/>I don't see how that law really applies here.  An equally lit object 100 miles away should be just as bright as one 10 feet away, if you ignore the effects of impurities in the atmosphere.<BR/><BR/>Sure the *quantity* of light is smaller at 100 miles, but so is the area the object occupies on your retina.  So the brightness should be the same, no?
</p>
</dd>
